# Workspace Conventions

## Source of truth — native vs shared

AI configuration comes from two distinct origins that must not be confused:

**mAIcelium-native** — lives directly in the mAIcelium repo and is intrinsic
to this workspace. There is no "source" elsewhere. Write and commit here.

```
mesh/rules/<name>.mdc              ← native rule
mesh/skills/<name>/SKILL.md        ← native skill (flat; no _common/_domains/_clients)
mesh/commands/<name>.md            ← slash command
mesh/commands/scripts/<name>.py    ← command script
mesh/prompts/<name>.md             ← prompt template
mesh/mcp/<name>.json               ← MCP server definition
bin/**                             ← workspace tooling (hooks, sync, lifecycle)
```

**Shared (layer-managed)** — lives in an external repo mounted under
`mesh/layers/<layer>/`. The content is reflected into `mesh/` through two
tiers of symlinks managed by `bin/sync_symlinks.sh`:

```
mesh/layers/<layer>/skills|rules/...   ← TIER 1 source of truth (layer repo, own .git)
         ↓  (symlink)
mesh/{skills,rules}/{_common,_domains,_clients}/...   ← tier-1 reflection (gitignored)
         ↓  (symlink)
.cursor/, .agents/, .claude/...                       ← tier-2 reflection (IDE dotfolders)
```

Everything under `mesh/skills/{_common,_domains,_clients}/…` and
`mesh/rules/{_domains,_clients}/…` is a reflection of a layer and MUST be
edited at the layer path, never at the reflection path.

## Layer vs reflection — where to edit (decision tree)

Before editing a rule or skill, resolve its true source:

1. Is the path under `mesh/skills/{_common,_domains,_clients}/…` or
   `mesh/rules/{_domains,_clients}/…`?
   - **No** → it is a mAIcelium-native resource (e.g. `mesh/rules/global.mdc`,
     `mesh/skills/workspace-guide/SKILL.md`). Edit directly; commit in the
     mAIcelium repo.
   - **Yes** → continue.
2. Resolve the real path:
   ```bash
   python3 -c "import os,sys; print(os.path.realpath(sys.argv[1]))" <file>
   ```
   - If the realpath is under `mesh/layers/<layer>/…` → the reflection is a
     proper symlink; editing the reflection path transparently writes the layer
     file. Allowed, but prefer the layer path explicitly and commit in the
     **layer repo** (each layer has its own `.git`), not in mAIcelium.
   - If the realpath is still under `mesh/skills/…` or `mesh/rules/…` → it is
     a **stale real reflection** (drift). DO NOT edit it here. Port the change
     to the matching `mesh/layers/<layer>/…` path, commit inside the layer
     repo, then run `bin/sync_symlinks.sh --fix-drift` to convert the
     reflection into a proper symlink.
3. If unsure which layer owns the content, list `mesh/layers/` and search for
   the matching relative path. Every entry under
   `_common|_domains|_clients` maps 1:1 to
   `mesh/layers/<layer>/skills/{_common,_domains}/<name>` or
   `mesh/layers/<layer>/skills/<client-name>` for client entries.

The `guard-write.sh` PreToolUse hook enforces this: writes to stale reflections
are blocked and the agent is redirected to the correct layer path.

## Naming

- Files and directories: **kebab-case** (e.g., `code-review`, `security-checklist.mdc`).
- Project-prefixed symlinks use `--` as separator (e.g., `my-api--custom-rule.mdc`).

## Command output

Slash command responses must end with a single emoji-prefixed status line:
- ✅/✔ success — ⚠️ warning — ❌ error — ❓ ambiguous — 🗑️ removed — 📭 empty

## File placement quick reference

| What                              | Where (canonical source of truth)                                        |
|-----------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Global rule (mAIcelium-native)    | `mesh/rules/<name>.mdc`                                                  |
| Native skill (mAIcelium-native)   | `mesh/skills/<name>/SKILL.md`                                            |
| Domain rule (shared)              | `mesh/layers/<layer>/rules/_domains/<domain>/<name>.mdc`                 |
| Client rule (shared)              | `mesh/layers/<layer>/rules/<name>.mdc` (layer's name maps to its client) |
| Universal skill (shared)          | `mesh/layers/<layer>/skills/_common/<name>/SKILL.md`                     |
| Domain skill (shared)             | `mesh/layers/<layer>/skills/_domains/<domain>/<name>/SKILL.md`           |
| Client skill (shared)             | `mesh/layers/<layer>/skills/<name>/SKILL.md`                             |
| MCP definition                    | `mesh/mcp/<name>.json`                                                   |
| Command                           | `mesh/commands/<name>.md`                                                |
| Script                            | `mesh/commands/scripts/<name>.py`                                        |
| Prompt template                   | `mesh/prompts/<name>.md`                                                 |

A skill or rule is **mAIcelium-native** when it describes the workspace
itself (architecture, conventions, hooks, slash commands, migrations) — it
has no meaning outside this repo and must not live in a shared layer.
Examples: `workspace-guide`, `cursor-workspace-migration`,
`workspace-conventions`, `maicelium-identity`.

A skill or rule is **shared** when it encodes reusable knowledge that could
be consumed by any mAIcelium-style workspace — engineering practices,
domain playbooks, client-specific runbooks. These belong to a layer.

The paths under `mesh/{skills,rules}/{_common,_domains,_clients}/…` are
reflections only — `.gitignore` excludes them from the mAIcelium repo on
purpose. Edit the layer, commit in the layer repo, then run
`bin/sync_symlinks.sh`.

## MCP configuration

MCP server definitions live in `mesh/mcp/<name>.json`. Each file is IDE-agnostic:

```json
{
  "name": "server-name",
  "description": "What this MCP does",
  "projects": ["project-name"],
  "config": {
    "type": "http",
    "url": "https://mcp.example.com/v1/mcp"
  }
}
```

`sync_symlinks.sh` generates IDE-specific files from these definitions:
- `.mcp.json` → Claude Code (project-scoped, picked up automatically)
- `.cursor/mcp.json` → Cursor workspace-level
- `.agents/mcp.json` → Antigravity

All three are auto-generated and gitignored. Each IDE authenticates its own OAuth session
independently — credentials are never stored in `mesh/`.

## Auto-generated files (do not edit)

- `WORKSPACE.md` — updated by `bin/add_project.sh` / `bin/remove_project.sh`
- `.claude/projects-context.md` — regenerated by `bin/_lib.sh` (inlines workspace + project rules)
- `.cursor/rules/*` — symlinks created by `bin/init.sh` / `bin/sync_symlinks.sh`
- `.cursor/skills-cursor/*` — symlinks created by `bin/init.sh` / `bin/sync_symlinks.sh`
- `.cursor/mcp.json` — generated by `bin/sync_symlinks.sh` from `mesh/mcp/`
- `.agents/rules/*` — symlinks created by `bin/sync_symlinks.sh`
- `.agents/skills/*` / `.agents/workflows/*` — symlinks created by `bin/sync_symlinks.sh`
- `.agents/mcp.json` — generated by `bin/sync_symlinks.sh` from `mesh/mcp/`
- `.mcp.json` — generated by `bin/sync_symlinks.sh` from `mesh/mcp/` (Claude Code)
- `mesh/{skills,rules}/{_common,_domains,_clients}/*` — layer reflections materialized by `bin/sync_symlinks.sh`; the source of truth lives in `mesh/layers/<layer>/`

## Layer drift

When `bin/sync_symlinks.sh` finds a reflection that is a real file/directory
instead of a symlink (typically leftover content from before the layer model),
it prints a drift report at the end of the run and takes no destructive
action. Two outcomes:

- **identical drift** — reflection matches the layer byte-for-byte. Re-run
  `bin/sync_symlinks.sh --fix-drift` to replace it with a symlink.
- **divergent drift** — reflection and layer differ. Resolve manually: port
  the delta into the layer path, commit in the layer repo, remove the stale
  reflection, then re-run the sync.

Never overwrite divergent drift blindly — it usually means a prior agent edited
the reflection instead of the layer.
